ense terms for the project.\n\n11. **./README.md:** Provides an overview of the project, including how to use or contribute to it.\n\n### High-Level Architecture:\nBased on the repository structure and file content, the project seems to be a large-scale, distributed benchmarking system. It uses AWS extensively and seems to consist of various microservices or components, each with a specific role. The system likely uses a microservices architecture, where each service or component is developed, deployed, and scaled independently.\n\nThe system seems to make extensive use of Docker for containerization, allowing for easy deployment and scaling. It also appears to use AWS services, such as AWS ECS for container orchestration and AWS ECR for Docker image storage.\n\nThe project also seems to follow DevOps principles, with CI/CD pipelines in place, and infrastructure managed as code using Terraform.\n\n### Overall Summary:\nThe repository "benchmark-ai" is a large-scale, cloud-based benchmarking system designed by AWS Labs. It\'s organized as a collection of microservices, each serving a specific purpose in the system.\n\nThe architecture is robust and scalable, using Docker for containerization and AWS services for orchestration, storage, and more. The project also adheres to DevOps principles, with CI/CD pipelines and infrastructure-as-code practices.\n\nEach component or service in the system has its own directory in the repository, containing the necessary code, configuration, and test files. The repository also includes comprehensive documentation, providing insights into the system\'s design and operation.\n\nOverall, the repository is a well-structured, complex project showcasing best practices in cloud-native application development, containerization, microservices architecture, and DevOps.'}
